story.title: Falco - Episode 9
story.storyDescription: Libby Dixon is missing. Will Agent Falco crack the case?
story.creator: web-uploader
story.prePaywallNotification: WHAT?! Libby was seeing her sister’s ex-boyfriend?! Does that mean that he killed Libby? 🔪 Tap back into Hooked to find out.
story.postPaywallNotification: Uh-oh. Jimmy Fitz just asked for a lawyer to help him during police questioning. Does that mean he killed Libby Dixon? 😡😡 Tap back into Hooked to find out.

messages.text: Investigation: Day 10.
The following is a transcript of an interview between Agent Falco, Deputy Decker, and Jimmy Fitz, recorded June 29, 9:31 AM.
Please state your name and occupation for the record.
Jimmy Fitz. I’m a mechanic, like my dad.
Do I need a lawyer for this?
You could get a lawyer, but we won’t be able to talk to you anymore if you do.
If you help us out and answer some questions…
We can tell the DA you’ve been cooperative.
The DA?
That’s the District Attorney, son.
You’re full of it.
You’ve got nothing on me ‘cause I didn’t do nothing.
We’ve got your DNA, Jimmy.
And we tested it against the fetal DNA in Libby Dixon.
Do you know what that word means — “fetal?”
Oh.
Jimmy slumps in his chair a little and wipes the sweat off of his forehead with a grease-stained shirt sleeve.
You’re talking about the baby, aren’t you?
You knew Libby was pregnant?
Yeah. She told me.
But I swear I didn’t hurt her — you have to believe me.
You’re 22, aren’t you, Jimmy?
Yeah.
Libby was 16—
The fetal DNA inside her proves you had sexual intercourse with a minor.
That’s statutory rape.
So what happened?
She threatened to tell?
You wanted her to get an abortion but she wouldn’t, so you killed her?
Jimmy sits up suddenly, his eyes darting back and forth between Deputy Decker and Agent Falco.
What? No.
She wanted to get the abortion.
Is that why she had the fake ID?
No. She got that so she could drink.
Couldn’t you buy her booze?
Yeah, but we liked to go to bars sometimes.
You weren’t recognized at these bars?
No, ‘cause we’d drive over to Newbury, or sometimes Pottsville.
You know, ‘cause we couldn’t be seen together in Cedar Creek.
She couldn’t use her fake ID here — everybody knows her.
Do you know where she got the fake ID, Jimmy?
I bought it for her. I know a guy who makes ‘em.
Who’s Emily Baker?
Nobody.
Libby picked that name.
I want to back up to the beginning.
You were dating Libby’s sister, Anna Mae.
Yeah, Anna Mae’s really hot.
But she was obsessed with me.
I don’t like clingy.
You broke up with her on several occasions, correct?
Yeah. But she’d always beg me to come back.
She’d show up at my house in the middle of the night in her underwear and a trench coat.
That’s not easy to resist, you know.
So when did you start sleeping with Libby?
I was leaving their house one night in early April.
I’d been hanging out with Anna Mae, watching some shitty chick flick…
And on my way out, I saw Libby on the front porch.
I knew she’d been in the hospital, so I asked how she was doing.
She told me all about Duke Simmons — it just poured out of her.
I felt bad for her. I mean, she’s really sweet, and much less needy than Anna Mae.
And she’s pretty hot herself—
She looks a hell of a lot like Anna Mae.
I guess things sort of took off from there, you know?
So you were the white knight saving the poor damsel in distress?
I don’t know — she just needed someone to talk to.
She told me I made her so happy that all she wanted was me.
But Libby didn’t break up with Duke until May.
She wanted to wait ‘til school was out.
So she wouldn’t have to see him in class all the time.
It got too hard for her, though — she dumped him the last week of school, I think it was.
Said she couldn’t wait anymore.
But you didn’t break up with Anna Mae ‘til a few weeks ago?
Yeah, on June 4.
I needed to keep dating her so I’d have an excuse to come over and see Libby.
But Libby thought it was enough to meet up at motels and bars out of town.
I didn’t think her flimsy excuse about sleeping over at her friend Rachel's house would hold up, but I fell hard for Libby.
So I finally dumped Anna Mae.
Okay, and when did Libby tell you she was pregnant?
June 18.
That’s the day she disappeared — this looks really bad for you, Jimmy.
I need you to tell us what happened at The Junction.
Did you kill her to keep her quiet about the baby?
Did she have a terrible accident, maybe?
Jimmy shakes his head sadly and chokes back a sob.
No, no. None of those things.
She was alive when I left her.
We didn’t even end up having sex.
We just talked about what she should do next.
Did Libby tell you she wanted an abortion?
Yeah, but she was scared. She had the fake ID, and I said I’d give her the money…
But I think she felt really guilty about it, you know—
She was really religious.
What did she tell you she wanted to do?
She wanted to come clean to her mom—
She said her mom would help her out and keep it from her dad.
But why not get the abortion with the fake ID?
She was really pro-life and all that.
I guess she wanted to talk to her mom and get her advice.
Did she tell you when she found out about the pregnancy?
She said she knew for sure when she took the pregnancy test.
But I think she had a feeling about it before that.
When did she take the test?
The day before, I think.
That explains why she seemed upset during her shift at Scoops that evening.
But Libby didn’t talk to her mother, Jimmy.
Yeah, ‘cause she disappeared before she could. I didn’t know about it, obviously…
That’s why I texted her.
You’re the “Bronco” who texted, asking if she did it.
Yeah, I wanted to know if she told her mom.
Why did you go by a codename?
I didn’t want my real name in our texts since her dad goes through her phone sometimes.
So why “Bronco?”
It was the first model car I worked on with my dad as a kid.
She thought it was cute, so we went with it, you know.
Jimmy tilts his head to the side and smiles half-heartedly.
Let’s back up a little, okay?
She wanted to get her mother’s advice about the pregnancy.
Her mom would probably ask who the father was, right?
And you didn’t have a problem with her revealing your identity?
She said she’d tell her mom the baby was Duke’s.
She never actually hooked up with that bastard, but her mom didn’t know that.
Libby said she’d tell her mom not to talk to the Simmons about it—
And Lynnette wouldn’t, ‘cause she knows Duke’s an abusive asshole with a history of violence.
Then Libby would get the abortion — and no one would know it was my kid or whatever.
And you trusted her enough to tell her mother all this?
It’s a pretty big secret.
It was her secret, too.
And her body.
Unlike the Dixons, I’m not really religious.
I think it should be the woman’s choice.
So you’re saying you gallantly allowed Libby to choose your fate?
And that she left The Junction alive?
Yeah, pretty much.
Assuming you’re telling us the truth, when did you find out that Libby was missing?
That evening—
Anna Mae called me in hysterics, begging me to help her.
You didn’t attempt to reach Libby after she disappeared?
Anna Mae said the cops had Libby’s phone.
I’m not stupid — I know she’s a minor.
You were the last one to see Libby Dixon alive, Mr. Fitz.
Agent Falco leans over the table, close enough to smell the alcohol on Jimmy’s breath.
You fathered her unborn child.
Jimmy scoots his chair back, the metal legs scraping against the concrete floor of the interview room.
Okay, you know what?
I want a lawyer.
We can’t talk to you anymore if you ask for an attorney, Jimmy.
Jimmy folds his arms across his chest and frowns.
Lawyer.
Okay, fine. Enjoy your lethal injection when the jury finds out you murdered a pregnant teen.
This interview is over.
The following is a text message conversation between Deputy Decker and Agent Falco, initiated June 29, 10:18 PM.
You awake, Agent?
Yeah.
I can’t really sleep.
Keep thinking about Cate.
What if she gets involved with a man like Jimmy Fitz when she’s older?
I can’t imagine this happening to my little girl.
I know — I would feel the same if I had a child.
But that’s not in the cards for me.
You sure? You seem pretty young still.
I mean, you could have children if you wanted to.
I’m 38, but I know I can’t have them.
It’s just…I was engaged once. His name was Charlie.
We couldn’t seem to conceive, so we went to see a doctor…
We found out I’m infertile.
I’m so sorry, Frankie.
Charlie was really supportive for a while, but he couldn’t take it.
Each time he saw a child, his heart broke. And eventually…
He bolted. Everyone does in the end, don’t they?
Daisy left me too, yeah.
But I’d like to think I could find love again.
I’m not really looking for it, I guess.
Is that why you decided to become a Special Agent?
To work alone?
To avoid love?
To be honest—
My mother was shot and killed during a bad drug deal when I was in college.
That’s when I decided to enter law enforcement.
That’s terrible. I’m sorry.
I didn’t really know her.
I grew up in a series of foster homes, some more abusive than others.
You were taken by Children’s Services?
When I was five, yeah.
Dad split before I was born.
Mom’s new boyfriend broke her jaw in three places…
And then she got hooked on prescription painkillers.
When those ran out, she started shooting up heroin instead.
Kind of paints a bleak picture, doesn’t it?
But you made it out.
I worked my ass off to get a college scholarship.
Tuition and expenses paid in full, thanks to cross country.
I get it. I took classes online to get my criminal justice degree while on the job.
The tuition broke the bank.
Speaking of college, I know why Simmons didn’t want us talking to Duke.
Because he was protecting his son?
Yeah, but it was more than that—
Duke had an alibi.
Apparently, he was caught shoplifting a video game the morning of June 18.
He was being held in Newbury ‘til his father came to smooth things over.
Duke wasn’t released until 8 PM—
After Lynette called 911 to report her daughter missing.
I don’t understand.
Why wouldn’t Simmons just tell us that to begin with?
He knows how rumors spread around here…
So he didn’t want the incriminating information out in the open when Duke was applying to colleges.
And I doubt he wanted you to know how much he abuses his power.
Interesting. Check with Newbury police to verify Duke’s alibi?
But otherwise, I think we should focus our efforts on Jimmy Fitz.
I’d like to talk to Anna Mae about him.
Schedule her for an interview tomorrow morning at the Sheriff’s Office.
Roger that, boss.
I’ll see you in the AM.
Goodnight, Frankie.
Goodnight, Tex.
